# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alpine-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alpine-linux/alpine-linux] Originally, Alpine Linux began as an embedded-first distribution for devices such as wireless routers, based on Gentoo Linux, inspired by GNAP and the Bering-uClibc branch of the LEAF Project.
[src:alpine-linux/alpine-linux] Founder Natanael Copa has said that the name was chosen as a backronym for "A Linux-Powered Network Engine" or some such similar phrase, but that the exact phrase has since been forgotten.
[src:alpine-linux/alpine-linux] Alpine's package management system, the Alpine Package Keeper (apk), was originally a collection of shell scripts but was later rewritten in C.
[src:alpine-linux/alpine-linux] In 2014, Alpine Linux switched from uClibc to musl as its C standard library.
[src:alpine-linux/alpine-linux] postmarketOS, a Linux distribution for mobile devices, is based on Alpine Linux.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Originally written by Bruce Perens in 1995 and declared complete for his intended usage in 1996, BusyBox initially aimed to put a complete bootable system on a single floppy disk that would serve both as a rescue disk and as an installer for the Debian distribution.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Since that time, it has been extended to become the de facto standard core user space toolset for embedded Linux devices and Linux distribution installers.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Since each Linux executable requires several kilobytes of overhead, having the BusyBox program combine over two hundred programs together often saves substantial disk space and system memory.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox was maintained by Enrique Zanardi and focused on the needs of the Debian boot-floppies installer system until early 1998, when Dave Cinege took it over for the Linux Router Project (LRP).
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Cinege made several additions, created a modularized build environment, and shifted BusyBox's focus into general high-level embedded systems.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] As LRP development slowed down in 1999, Erik Andersen, then of Lineo, Inc., took over the project and became the official maintainer between December 1999 and March 2006.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] During this time the Linux embedded marketplace exploded in growth, and BusyBox matured greatly, expanding both its user base and functionality.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Rob Landley became the maintainer in 2005 until late 2006, then Denys Vlasenko took over as the current maintainer.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] In September 2006, after heavy discussions and controversies between project maintainer Rob Landley and Bruce Perens, the BusyBox project decided against adopting the GNU General Public License Version 3 (GPLv3), and announced an intent to have the BusyBox license be GPLv2-only.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Since October 2006, Denys Vlasenko has taken over maintainership of BusyBox from Rob Landley, who has started Toybox, also as a result of the license controversies.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] In late 2007, BusyBox also came to prominence for actively prosecuting violations of the terms of its license (the GPL) in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] What was claimed to be the first US lawsuit over a GPL violation concerned the use of BusyBox in an embedded device.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The lawsuit, case 07-CV-8205, was filed on September 20, 2007, by the Software Freedom Law Center (SFLC) on behalf of Andersen and Landley against Monsoon Multimedia Inc., after BusyBox code was discovered in a firmware upgrade and attempts to contact the company had apparently failed.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The case was settled with release of the Monsoon version of the source and payment of an undisclosed amount of money to Andersen and Landley.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] On November 21, 2007, the SFLC brought two similar lawsuits on behalf of Andersen and Landley against two more companies, Xterasys (case 07-CV-10455) and High-Gain Antennas (case 07-CV-10456).
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The Xterasys case was settled on December 17 for release of source code used and an undisclosed payment, and the High-Gain Antennas case on March 6, 2008, for active license compliance and an undisclosed payment.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Further suits were brought on June 9, 2008, against Bell Microproducts (case 08-CV-5270) and SuperMicro (case 08-CV-5269), with the Super Micro case being settled on July 23, 2008.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox and Bell Microproducts also settled out of court on October 17.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] On December 14, 2009, a new lawsuit was filed naming fourteen defendants including Best Buy, JVC, Samsung and others.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] In February 2010 Samsung released its LN52A650 TV firmware under GPLv2, which was used later as a reference by the SamyGO community project.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] On about August 3, 2010, BusyBox won from Westinghouse a default judgement of triple damages of $90,000 and lawyers' costs and fees of $47,865, and possession of "presumably a lot of high-def TVs" as infringing equipment in the lawsuit Software Freedom Conservancy v.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Best Buy, et al., the GPL infringement case noted in the paragraph above.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] No other developers, including original author Bruce Perens and maintainer Dave Cinege, were represented in these actions or party to the settlements.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Toybox was started early 2006 under the GPL-2.0-only license by former BusyBox maintainer Rob Landley as a result of the controversies around GPLv3/GPLv2 discussions.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] At the end of 2011 it was relicensed under the BSD-2-Clause license after the project went dormant.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] In March 2013, it was relicensed again under the 0BSD license.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] On January 11, 2012, Tim Bird, a Sony employee, suggested creating an alternative to BusyBox which would not be under the GNU General Public License.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] He suggested it be based on the dormant Toybox.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] In January 2012 the proposal of creating a BSD licensed alternative to the GPL licensed BusyBox project drew harsh criticism from Matthew Garrett for taking away the only relevant tool for copyright enforcement of the Software Freedom Conservancy group.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The starter of BusyBox based lawsuits, Rob Landley, responded that this was intentional as he came to the conclusion that the lawsuits resulted not in the hoped for positive outcomes and he wanted to stop them "in whatever way I see fit".
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox can be customized to provide a subset of over two hundred utilities.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] It can provide most of the utilities specified in the Single Unix Specification (SUS) plus many others that a user would expect to see on a Linux system.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox uses the Almquist shell, also known as A Shell, ash and sh.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] An alternative for customization is the smaller 'hush' shell.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] As it is a complete bootstrap system, it will further replace the init daemon and udev (or the latter-day systemd) using itself to be called as *init* on startup and *mdev* at hotplug time.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The BusyBox website provides a full list of the utilities implemented.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Typical computer programs have a separate binary (executable) file for each application.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox is a single binary, which is a conglomerate of many applications, each of which can be accessed by calling the single BusyBox binary with various names (supported by having a symbolic link or hard link for each different name) in a specific manner with appropriate arguments.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Sharing of the common code, along with routines written with size-optimization in mind, can make a BusyBox system use much less storage space than a system built with the corresponding full versions of the utilities replaced by BusyBox.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Research that compared GNU, BusyBox, asmutils and Perl implementations of the standard Unix commands showed that in some situations BusyBox may perform faster than other implementations, but not always.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The official BusyBox documentation lists an overview of the available commands and their command-line options.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] A command can be run by prefixing a command line with a path to the BusyBox executable.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] Commonly, each command is exposed as a hard or symbolic link to the BusyBox executable.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] For example, if `/bin/ls` links to `/bin/busybox` then the program name command-line argument is "/bin/ls" and BusyBox treats it as the `ls` command.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox is used by several operating systems running on embedded systems and is an essential component of distributions such as OpenWrt, OpenEmbedded (including the Yocto Project) and Buildroot.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] The Sharp Zaurus utilizes BusyBox extensively for ordinary Unix-like tasks performed on the system's shell.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] BusyBox is also an essential component of VMware ESXi, Tiny Core Linux, SliTaz 5(Rolling), and Alpine Linux, none of which are embedded distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/busybox] It is necessary for several root applications on Android and is also preinstalled with some "1 Tap Root" solutions such as Kingo Root.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:alpine-linux/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] musl was designed from scratch to allow efficient static linking and to have realtime-quality robustness by avoiding race conditions, internal failures on resource exhaustion, and various other bad worst-case behaviors present in existing implementations.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] The dynamic runtime is a single file with stable ABI allowing race-free updates and the static linking support allows an application to be deployed as a single portable binary without significant size overhead.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] It claims compatibility with the POSIX 2008 specification and the C11 standard.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] It also implements most of the widely used non-standard Linux, BSD, and glibc functions.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] There is partial ABI compatibility with the part of glibc required by Linux Standard Base.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] A modified version of musl is available for userspace code written for the seL4 microkernel, requiring users to implement the parts of the Linux system call interface that the subset of musl they wish to use depends on.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] Huawei's HarmonyOS NEXT operating system uses a fork of musl as its libc implementation.
[src:alpine-linux/musl] For binaries that have been linked against glibc, gcompat and glibmus-hq can be used to execute them on musl-based distros.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] OpenRC is made up of several modular components, the main ones being an init (optional), the core dependency management system, and a daemon supervisor (optional).
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] It is written in C and POSIX-compliant shell, making it usable on BSD and Linux systems.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] The core part of OpenRC handles dependency management and init script parsing.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] OpenRC works by scanning the runlevels, building a dependency graph, then starting the needed service scripts.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] It exits once the scripts have been started.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] By default, OpenRC uses a modified version of start-stop-daemon for daemon management.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] Init scripts share similarities with scripts used in sysvinit, but offer several features to simplify their creation.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] Scripts are assumed to have `start()`, `stop()` and `status()`; and the system uses variables already declared to create the default functions.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] The depend function is used to declare dependencies to other services that would be done with LSB headers in sysvinit.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] Configuration and mechanism are separated with configuration files in the conf.d directory and init files in the init.d directory.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] openrc-init first appeared in version 0.25 as an optional replacement for `/sbin/init`.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] This can replace Gentoo Linux's default init system, sysvinit.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] Supervise-daemon first appeared in version 0.21 giving OpenRC supervision capabilities.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] It can be enabled in the init script for supervise-daemon to start and monitor a daemon.
[src:alpine-linux/openrc] Several other daemon supervisors are supported, including runit and s6.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:alpine-linux/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
